The study addresses the challenge of multiple operationalisations by using an adaptive design to find the method that provides the strongest evidence. All method start equally probable, but probability of assignment changes with the strength of evidence as the study progresses.

PSA005 addresses the challenge of low power due to relatively rare populations by collecting data from many researchers, all in the US. Recruitment has been disrupted by COVID, but there will be at least 2000 participants. https://t.co/Q1nhkMCIuF

Each type can have many different methods and combinations, leading to 224 potential operationalisations. Combined with low-power studies, it is difficult to make firm conclusions. https://t.co/6pwdpSotzJ

Studies have increased threat using four types of manipulations:

A. Make task evaluative
B. Claim group differences
C. Stereotype-relevant primes
D. Interpersonal threats

Studies have decreased threat using four types of manipulations:

1. Make task non-diagnostic
2. Refute group differences
3. Intrapsychic strategies
4. Situational strategies

Studies tend to have low precision, with a median N of 52. Only 6% of students at US research-active institutions are Black.

Stereotype threat is operationalised in different ways. This may lead to differences in study conclusions.

This research has policy implications. For example, stereotype threat research has been cited in US Supreme Court cases (Fisher vs U Texas Austin). However, the evidence for stereotype threat is challenged by problems common to social psych...

Stereotype threat is feelings of threat that arise from the possibility of confirming a negative group stereotype. There are hundreds of studies on this, especially around the "achievement gap" between Black and white students in the US.

Project-based funding doesn't work well with the timelines that a large-scale collaboration needs, but funders are reluctant to fund unknown future projects. Funding is also needed for stable archiving of the data from these projects.

The lack of dedicated, long-term funding leads to worries about sustainability. Both ManyBabies and PSA have experienced bureaucratic barriers to distributing small pots of money internationally to collaborating labs.

The topic of funding is complicated for #BigTeamScience. @BrRepInitiative started with philanthropic funding, @PsySciAcc took 4 years to get any major funding, @ManyPrimates has one award through a partnership with #ManyBabies. Most projects rely on volunteer contributions.
It sounds like all the groups could use more collaborators who do things like analysis planning, data quality checks, data wrangling, and code check.

Much like ManyBabies and @PsySciAcc, @ManyPrimates doesn't require you to collect data to be involved. There are many opportunities to help analyse data or do other tasks. @BrRepInitiative would like more non-data-collection contributions.

There is no way to track exactly what everyone is doing across a big project, so projects have to rely on trust. Long-term projects also have some attrition from people moving institutions, students graduating, and even people leaving academia.

Tracking contributions: ManyBabies1 used a consortium authorship, but now use individual authorship to make sure everyone can demonstrate authorship.

A related point was how team science is valued by institutions. Most institutions (regardless of region) don't place high enough value on team science. We could create more sub-projects with opportunities to publish things like methods and translation reports with smaller teams.

Another point was linguistic barriers. Possible solutions might be more written/recorded training, large-scale translation efforts, or train-the-trainers sessions so people can develop language-specific resources.

One point we wondered was whether people have misconceptions about how much knowledge is required to join a PSA project. There are many tasks required for each project, requiring many different skills, but almost any researcher has some needed skills.
The group I was in discussed training and resource availability. What are the major training/knowledge barriers to joining a team science project for non-Western researchers?

* There have yet been senior influencer(s) in non-WEIRD countries to boost team science.
* Lack of relevance for the project topic in the country/region

* Lack of formal training for non-WEIRD psychologists to conduct a collaborative project.
* Lack of workshops/programs beyond one's school that are easily accessible  
* Open science practices have yet been norms in non-WEIRD academics.
>

My use case was wanting to count tweets by hashtag using the lowercase version of the hashtag, but to display the result with the most common version of the hashtag. A custom function might be too complex for the intro example I'm writing, so simpler solutions are welcome.
Caveat: doesn't deal with ties (but could be modified to do so) and probably already exists somewhere in dplyr, but I couldn't find it after a 5-minute search, so made my own function.

#rtips Find the most/least common value(s):

common <- function(x, n = 1, type="most") {
  dir <- type == "most"
  sort_x <- sort(table(x), dir)
  names(sort_x)[1:n]
}

group_by(diamonds, cut) %>%
summarise(
  commonest = common(color),
  rarest = common(color, 1, "least")
)
